14 WHEREAS, she made history as the first African American city councilwoman of Fairburn,
15 serving with distinction for 12 years and earning accolades such as the Council Member
16 Outstanding Service Award and the Legacy Trailblazer Award in recognition of her lasting
17 contributions; and
18 WHEREAS, she was further invited to multiple presidential inaugural ceremonies, including
19 those of Presidents Bill Clinton, George W. Bush, and Barack Obama, and was the recipient
20 of both the Commemorative Presidential Print Award and the National Resource Defense
21 Council Award; and
22 WHEREAS, a woman of boundless generosity and warmth, she was known for her
23 hospitality, her legendary home-cooked Sunday dinners, and her ability to make anyone feel
24 like family; and
25 WHEREAS, she found joy in nurturing both her community and her garden, winning Yard
26 of the Year multiple times and transforming her front yard into an unwritten landmark in
27 Fairburn; and
28 WHEREAS, she was united in love and marriage to her husband, Lawrence, and together
29 they were blessed with seven remarkable children, Lawrence, Alford Sr., Jane, Shanterria,
30 Cheryl, Bobby, and Kimberly, as well as 22 wonderful grandchildren and four beloved
31 great-grandchildren; and
32 WHEREAS, a compassionate and devoted woman, Essie Frankie Mae Stegall Arnold will
33 long be remembered for her love of family, friendship, and community and will be missed
34 by all who had the great fortune of knowing her.
